1	\chapter{The relative Picard functor as an abelian-group-valued presheaf}
2	\label{chap:Picard_FunctorAb}
3	
4	This chapter is the natural successor to Chapter~\ref{chap:Picard_Functor}. The Lean realisation of the relative Picard functor in Chapter~\ref{chap:Picard_Functor} is $\Type$-valued (\lstinline{(Over (Spec k))ᵒᵖ ⥤ Type u}); the construction merely forgets the abelian-group structure that the values $\Pic(C \times_k S) / p_S^*\Pic(S)$ carry by definition. To set up Phase~C step~3 (étale sheafification, deferred) and any future cohomology-of-Picard-presheaf work, we need an $\AddCommGrpCat$-valued variant whose values agree on the nose with the $\Type$-valued ones.
5	
6	The chapter introduces no protected declarations: every definition and lemma here is auxiliary, supporting Chapter~\ref{chap:Jacobian} via the same path as Chapter~\ref{chap:Picard_Functor}.
7	
8	\section{Definition}
9	
10	\begin{definition}[Relative Picard functor, abelian-group valued]
11	  \label{def:Pic_functorAb}
12	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.PicardFunctorAb}
13	  \uses{def:Pic_functor}
14	  \leanok
15	  Let $C$ be a scheme over $\Spec k$. The \emph{abelian-group-valued relative Picard functor} of $C$ over $k$ is the contravariant functor
16	  \[
17	    \PicardFunctorAb\, C \;\colon\; (\Sch_k)^{\mathrm{op}} \;\longrightarrow\; \AddCommGrpCat,\qquad
18	    S \;\longmapsto\; \mathtt{AddCommGrpCat.of}\;\bigl(\Pic(C \times_k S) / p_S^*\Pic(S)\bigr),
19	  \]
20	  with morphisms induced by \lstinline{PicardFunctor.quotMap} (defined in Chapter~\ref{chap:Picard_Functor}) wrapped as \lstinline{AddCommGrpCat} morphisms via \lstinline{AddCommGrpCat.ofHom}.
21	\end{definition}
22	
23	\begin{remark}
24	  The underlying-set functor of $\PicardFunctorAb\, C$ agrees on the nose with the $\Type$-valued Picard functor of Chapter~\ref{chap:Picard_Functor}: Definition~\ref{def:Pic_functor} computes the same group quotient $\Pic(C \times_k S) / p_S^*\Pic(S)$ but discards the group structure. The forget-and-recover natural iso (Definition~\ref{def:PicardFunctorAb_forgetCompare} below) records this. It is needed to transport later results (e.g.\ representability) between the two flavours.
25	\end{remark}
26	
27	\section{Forget-and-recover natural iso}
28	
29	\begin{definition}[$\PicardFunctorAb$ recovers $\PicardFunctor$ along $\forget \AddCommGrpCat$]
30	  \label{def:PicardFunctorAb_forgetCompare}
31	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.PicardFunctorAb.forgetCompare}
32	  \uses{def:Pic_functorAb, def:Pic_functor}
33	  \leanok
34	  Let $C : \Sch_k$. Then there is a natural isomorphism of $\Type$-valued functors
35	  \[
36	    \PicardFunctorAb\, C \,\circ\, \forget \AddCommGrpCat \;\cong\; \PicardFunctor\, C
37	  \]
38	  in $(\Sch_k)^{\mathrm{op}} \to \Type u$.
39	\end{definition}
40	
41	\begin{proof}
42	  \uses{def:Pic_functorAb, def:Pic_functor}
43	  \leanok
44	  Both sides have the same $\mathtt{obj}$ at $S \in (\Sch_k)^{\mathrm{op}}$ — the quotient set $\Pic(C \times_k S) / p_S^*\Pic(S)$ — and the same $\mathtt{map}$ on morphisms — the quotient pull-back induced by \lstinline{PicardFunctor.quotMap}. The $\Additive$ wrapper introduced in the iter-004 closure of $\PicardFunctorAb$ is type-equal to its underlying multiplicative quotient, so $\forget \AddCommGrpCat \circ \PicardFunctorAb\, C$ and $\PicardFunctor\, C$ agree on the nose at the underlying-type level. The natural iso is therefore the identity natural transformation in disguise: the prover closure (probe-confirmed) is \lstinline{NatIso.ofComponents (fun _ => Iso.refl _) (by intros; rfl)}.
45	\end{proof}
46	
47	% NOTE: the iter-004 prover round implemented \lstinline{PicardFunctorAb} by wrapping the
48	% multiplicative quotient through \lstinline{Additive}: the value at \(S\) is
49	% \lstinline{AddCommGrpCat.of (Additive (Pic (C ×_k S) ⧸ ...))} and the action on
50	% morphisms is \lstinline{MonoidHom.toAdditive (PicardFunctor.quotMap C f.unop)} bundled via
51	% \lstinline{AddCommGrpCat.ofHom}. The underlying type is def-equal to the multiplicative
52	% quotient (\lstinline{Additive G} is the same type as \lstinline{G} as a Lean type), so the
53	% "agrees on the nose with PicardFunctor" remark above is correct at the type level; only the
54	% group-structure instance differs (additive vs. multiplicative). The
55	% \lstinline{PicardFunctorAb_forget_obj} simp lemma below records this object-level
56	% definitional identity.
57	
58	\begin{lemma}[Forget-evaluation simp lemma]
59	  \label{lem:PicardFunctorAb_forget_obj}
60	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.PicardFunctorAb_forget_obj}
61	  \uses{def:Pic_functorAb, def:PicardFunctorAb_forgetCompare}
62	  \leanok
63	  For every $S \in (\Sch_k)^{\mathrm{op}}$,
64	  \[
65	    (\forget\,\AddCommGrpCat).\mathrm{obj}\,\bigl((\PicardFunctorAb\, C).\mathrm{obj}\,S\bigr) \;=\; (\PicardFunctor\, C).\mathrm{obj}\,S.
66	  \]
67	\end{lemma}
68	
69	\begin{proof}
70	  \uses{def:Pic_functorAb, def:PicardFunctorAb_forgetCompare}
71	  \leanok
72	  Definitionally true: both sides are the underlying carrier of the quotient $\Pic(C \times_k S) / p_S^*\Pic(S)$. The closure is \lstinline{rfl}.
73	\end{proof}
74	
75	\section{Étale sheafification}
76	
77	Iteration~008 lands the étale-sheafified relative Picard functor on top of $\PicardFunctorAb$. The Mathlib gap that previously blocked this (\lstinline{HasSheafify} for the étale topology over $\Spec k$ valued in $\AddCommGrpCat$) closed in current Mathlib (iter-007 plan-agent re-probe). The only remaining gymnastic is universe-pinning: the inferable \lstinline{HasSheafify} is at value-universe $\AddCommGrpCat.\{u{+}1\}$, while the iter-004 $\PicardFunctorAb$ lands at $\AddCommGrpCat.\{u\}$; we bridge the gap by post-composing with $\AddCommGrpCat.\mathtt{uliftFunctor}$.
78	
79	\begin{definition}[Étale-sheafified relative Picard functor]
80	  \label{def:PicardFunctorAb_etaleSheafified}
81	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.PicardFunctorAb.etaleSheafified}
82	  \uses{def:Pic_functorAb}
83	  Let $C$ be a scheme over $\Spec k$. The \emph{étale-sheafified relative Picard functor} of $C$ over $k$ is the étale sheaf on $\Sch_k$ obtained by sheafifying $\PicardFunctorAb\, C$ post-composed with the natural universe lift $\AddCommGrpCat.\{u\} \to \AddCommGrpCat.\{u{+}1\}$:
84	  \[
85	    \PicardFunctorAb.\mathrm{etaleSheafified}\, C \;\colon\;
86	    \mathtt{Sheaf}\bigl(((\mathtt{Scheme.etaleTopology.}\{u\}).\mathtt{over}\,(\Spec\,(\mathtt{CommRingCat.of}\,k)))\,,\,\AddCommGrpCat.\{u{+}1\}\bigr).
87	  \]
88	\end{definition}
89	
90	\begin{proof}
91	  \uses{def:Pic_functorAb}
92	  Apply \lstinline{CategoryTheory.presheafToSheaf} (the Mathlib left-adjoint of the forgetful functor $\Sheaf \to \Pre$) to the universe-lifted presheaf. The probe-confirmed closure body is
93	  \begin{lstlisting}
94	  (CategoryTheory.presheafToSheaf _ _).obj
95	    (PicardFunctorAb C ⋙ AddCommGrpCat.uliftFunctor.{u+1, u}).
96	  \end{lstlisting}
97	  The two \lstinline{HasWeakSheafify} / \lstinline{HasSheafify} instances are now inferable in current Mathlib for the étale topology over $\Spec k$ valued in $\AddCommGrpCat.\{u{+}1\}$, so \lstinline{presheafToSheaf} types out without extra hypotheses.
98	\end{proof}
99	
100	\section{Use in the project}
101	
102	Definitions~\ref{def:Pic_functorAb} and~\ref{def:PicardFunctorAb_etaleSheafified} set up the codomain needed for:
103	
104	\begin{itemize}
105	  \item The étale-sheafified version of the relative Picard functor of Chapter~\ref{chap:Picard_Functor}: the input shape required by Grothendieck's representability machinery (FGA / Hilbert / Quot schemes) is a sheaf for the étale topology, not a presheaf. Definition~\ref{def:PicardFunctorAb_etaleSheafified} produces such a sheaf.
106	  \item Comparison with the Jacobian's $\Pic^0$ as a group scheme: the connected-component-of-identity of the representing scheme is a group object in $\Sch_k$; identifying $\PicardFunctorAb \cong \mathrm{HomFunctor}(\Pic_{C/k})$ via Yoneda is the cleanest path to the four \lstinline{Jacobian.lean} sorries.
107	  \item Direct definition of $H^n$-of-the-Picard-presheaf if a future iteration wants to expose it as a derived functor.
108	\end{itemize}
109	
110	The representability theorem \ref{thm:Pic_representable} of Chapter~\ref{chap:Picard_Functor} carries over verbatim once the étale sheafification of $\PicardFunctorAb$ has been constructed (Phase~C step~3, landed in iter-008); the four \lstinline{Jacobian.lean} sorries are the same as before, and the remaining gating obstruction for representability is the $\LineBundle$ refinement of Chapter~\ref{chap:Picard_LineBundle} (still blocked on absent $\MonoidalCategory$ on $X.\mathrm{Modules}$). This chapter does \emph{not} add a representability theorem of its own — the present chapter is the codomain change plus the étale sheafification.
111	
112	\section{Mathlib gap}
113	
114	Mathlib \texttt{b80f227} has every constituent for this chapter:
115	\begin{itemize}
116	  \item \lstinline{AddCommGrpCat.of}, \lstinline{AddCommGrpCat.ofHom} for wrapping a group / homomorphism into the bundled categorical shape.
117	  \item \lstinline{CommGroup} structure on \lstinline{Pic _ ⧸ _} via Mathlib's quotient-of-commutative-group machinery.
118	  \item This project's \lstinline{Picard.Functor} (Chapter~\ref{chap:Picard_Functor}, closed in iteration~004) for the underlying construction and the \lstinline{quotMap} functoriality.
119	\end{itemize}
120	
121	The chapter therefore introduces no new sorries beyond the single definition itself; the prover task is to wrap the Chapter~\ref{chap:Picard_Functor} construction in \lstinline{AddCommGrpCat} and discharge the resulting \lstinline{map\_id}/\lstinline{map\_comp} obligations (which reduce to those already proved for \lstinline{quotMap}).
122	
123	\section{Forward-compatibility note}
124	
125	The abelian-group-valued variant inherits the \lstinline{LineBundle} approximation from Chapter~\ref{chap:Picard_LineBundle}: the values on non-affine $S$ are smaller subgroups of the true relative Picard group. Étale sheafification of $\PicardFunctorAb$ would compose with this approximation on the codomain side; closing the eventual étale-sheafified representability sorry on the approximation is forbidden for the same reason as in Chapter~\ref{chap:Picard_Functor}. The deferred \lstinline{representable} of Chapter~\ref{chap:Picard_Functor} is the unique gating obstruction; this chapter neither widens nor narrows it.
126

